  "prompt": "How much of myoglobin is there in pork and how much of Iron is there in the myoglobin in weight?",
  "response": "Myoglobin is a heme-containing protein responsible for oxygen storage in muscle tissues. Its concentration can vary significantly among different types of meat. Here's a breakdown specific to pork:\n\n### **Myoglobin Content in Pork**\n\n- **Average Concentration:** Pork typically contains **approximately 40 milligrams (mg) of myoglobin per 100 grams (g) of muscle tissue**.\n  \n  - **Comparison with Other Meats:**\n    - **Beef:** ~100 mg/100g (higher myoglobin, redder color)\n    - **Chicken:** ~10 mg/100g (lower myoglobin, paler meat)\n\n### **Iron Content Within Myoglobin in Pork**\n\n- **Myoglobin Structure:** Each myoglobin molecule includes one heme group, which contains a single iron (Fe) atom.\n  \n- **Proportion of Iron by Weight in Myoglobin:**\n  - **Molecular Weight of Myoglobin:** ~17,000 grams per mole (g/mol)\n  - **Molecular Weight of Iron (Fe):** ~56 g/mol\n  - **Percentage Calculation:** \\( \\frac{56}{17,000} \\times 100 \\approx 0.33\\% \\)\n  \n- **Calculating Iron Content:**\n  - **Iron per 100g of Pork from Myoglobin:** \n    - \\( 40 \\text{ mg myoglobin} \\times 0.33\\% = 0.132 \\text{ mg iron} \\)\n  \n  - **Rounded Off:** Approximately **0.13 mg of iron** originates from myoglobin per 100 grams of pork.\n\n### **Summary**\n\n- **Myoglobin in Pork:** ~40\u202fmg per 100\u202fg of muscle.\n- **Iron from Myoglobin:** About 0.13\u202fmg of iron per 100\u202fg of pork.\n\nThese values can vary based on factors such as the specific cut of pork, the age of the animal, and its diet. Nonetheless, this provides a general estimate of myoglobin and its associated iron content in pork.",
